<p>Amylin is the appetite hormone almost nobody talks about. While GLP-1 gets the headlines, amylin has been quietly co-secreted with insulin by your pancreatic beta cells after every meal, helping regulate food intake through a completely separate pathway. Cagrilintide is Novo Nordisk's attempt to harness amylin's appetite-controlling power in a long-acting injectable peptide, and the early data suggests it fills a gap that GLP-1 drugs alone can't reach.</p>

<h2>Amylin: The Other Satiety Hormone</h2>

<p>When you eat, your pancreas releases insulin to manage blood glucose. At the same time, it co-secretes amylin, a 37-amino-acid peptide that works alongside insulin but through different mechanisms. Amylin slows gastric emptying (like GLP-1, but through different receptors). It suppresses glucagon secretion after meals. And it acts on the area postrema and other brainstem regions to produce satiety.</p>

<p>Natural amylin has a half-life of about 15 minutes, making it impractical as a medication. Pramlintide (Symlin), a synthetic amylin analog, was FDA-approved in 2005 for diabetes but required injection before every meal. Cagrilintide solves the pharmacokinetic problem: it's a lipidated amylin analog with a half-life long enough for once-weekly dosing.</p>

<h2>Cagrilintide Alone: What the Trials Show</h2>

<p>In a Phase 2 trial of 706 adults with overweight or obesity, cagrilintide monotherapy at the highest dose (4.5mg weekly) produced 10.8% weight loss over 26 weeks. All cagrilintide doses outperformed both placebo and the active comparator (liraglutide 3.0mg daily).</p>

<p>10.8% weight loss is meaningful, roughly matching liraglutide (the first-generation GLP-1 weight loss drug) in a shorter timeframe. But it's less than semaglutide or tirzepatide. The real value of cagrilintide isn't as a standalone treatment. It's what happens when you combine it with semaglutide.</p>

<h2>CagriSema: The Combination That Changes Everything</h2>

<p>Novo Nordisk's most anticipated pipeline product isn't cagrilintide alone. It's CagriSema: a fixed-dose combination of cagrilintide and semaglutide in a single weekly injection. The rationale is pharmacologically elegant: activate both the amylin and GLP-1 pathways simultaneously, producing appetite suppression through two independent mechanisms.</p>

<p>Phase 2 data for CagriSema showed approximately 17.1% weight loss at 32 weeks, exceeding what either component achieved alone. Phase 3 data is expected in 2026. Novo Nordisk has described CagriSema as having the potential to match or exceed bariatric surgery outcomes for weight loss, which would place it at 25-30% body weight reduction if the Phase 3 data scales from Phase 2 trends.</p>

<p>If CagriSema delivers on that promise, it becomes the first pharmaceutical treatment to genuinely rival surgical outcomes without surgery. That's the specific goal Novo Nordisk has set, and the Phase 2 data suggests it's achievable.</p>

<h2>How CagriSema Differs From Tirzepatide and Retatrutide</h2>

<p>CagriSema (amylin + GLP-1) hits different receptors than tirzepatide (GIP + GLP-1) or retatrutide (GIP + GLP-1 + glucagon). The appetite suppression comes from different brain regions and different signaling cascades.</p>

<p>In theory, these different receptor profiles could produce different patterns of weight loss, different side effect profiles, and different responder populations. Some patients who plateau on GLP-1 alone might respond to the addition of amylin agonism. Others might tolerate the amylin pathway better than the GIP pathway.</p>

<p>The competitive landscape is heading toward personalized selection: matching patients to the receptor combination that works best for their individual physiology, rather than one-size-fits-all prescribing.</p>

<h2>Side Effects</h2>

<p>Cagrilintide's side effect profile mirrors other appetite-suppressing peptides: nausea is the most common complaint, occurring in 25-40% of patients during dose escalation. Other GI effects (vomiting, diarrhea, constipation) occur at lower rates. Most symptoms are mild to moderate and resolve with continued use.</p>

<p>Amylin acts on the area postrema, the brainstem region that triggers nausea. This is the same mechanism that causes nausea with GLP-1 agonists, though through different receptors. Whether the combination (CagriSema) produces more or less nausea than either component alone is being assessed in Phase 3 trials. Phase 2 data suggested the combination was tolerable with appropriate dose escalation.</p>

<h2>Timeline and Access</h2>

<p>Cagrilintide is not FDA-approved as a standalone product. The development focus is on CagriSema (the combination with semaglutide). Phase 3 trials are ongoing with results expected in 2026. If positive, FDA submission would follow, with potential approval in 2027.</p>

<p>Novo Nordisk has positioned CagriSema as the successor to Wegovy (semaglutide) in their obesity portfolio. With semaglutide generating $29.3 billion in revenue in 2024, the commercial incentive to bring CagriSema to market is substantial.</p>

<p>For now, cagrilintide is a research compound available through limited channels. Most people interested in its effects would be better served by available GLP-1 options (semaglutide, tirzepatide) while monitoring CagriSema's Phase 3 development. If the combination delivers surgery-level weight loss in a weekly injection, it will redefine the obesity treatment landscape when it arrives.</p>
